A notification is only as good as where it takes the user. Learn how to implement deep linking for a seamless navigation experience.
It’s not just about the alert
So you’ve got notifications working. Great. But what happens when the user taps on it? If your app just opens to the home screen every time, you’re missing out on a huge part of the user experience. You want to send them exactly where the action is. If someone likes their photo, the notification should take them to that specific photo, not just the main feed. This is where deep linking and navigation state handling come in, and it’s where things can get a bit tricky.
Handling the initial notification
There are three states you need to worry about. The app is in the foreground, the app is in the background, or the app is completely closed (quit state). Handling the quit state is the one that usually trips people up. You have to use getInitialNotification to check if the app was opened via a notification press. If it was, you grab the data from that message and tell your navigator where to go once it’s ready.
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import messaging from '@react-native-firebase/messaging';
import { useNavigation } from '@react-navigation/native';const NotificationHandler = () => {
const navigation = useNavigation();
useEffect(() => {
// When the app is running in the background
messaging().onNotificationOpenedApp(remoteMessage => {
if (remoteMessage.data?.type === 'chat') {
navigation.navigate('Chat', { chatId: remoteMessage.data.id });
}
});
// When the app is opened from a quit state
messaging().getInitialNotification().then(remoteMessage => {
if (remoteMessage) {
// Handle the navigation here
}
});
}, []);
return null;
};
The importance of the data payload
When you send a notification from your Node.js backend, don’t just send a title and body. Use the data field. This is a key-value object where you can store IDs, URLs, or screen names. This data is invisible to the user but gold for your code. I always structure my payloads so the ‘type’ field tells the app which screen to open, and the ‘id’ field tells it what content to fetch. It makes the logic on the mobile side much cleaner.
Building this out properly takes a bit of planning. You need to make sure your navigation ref is ready before you try to jump to a screen. But honestly, the effort pays off. A well-implemented deep link makes an app feel intelligent and responsive. It’s those little details that separate a hobby project from a professional product. Keep testing those edge cases and you’ll get there.
